pullRequest.title: [risk=low][RW-4956] enable free credit limit override UX
pullRequest.bodyText:
Description:
Default case (no free tier credit limit override has been set yet) -> default values of 300-800 in dropdown

Existing override = 400 -> value of 400 is preselected, using the same default values

Existing override is not one of the default values -> this value is preselected and added to the dropdown choices, sorted appropriately. Examples for $234.50 and $1500



PR checklist

 This PR meets the Acceptance Criteria in the JIRA story
 The JIRA story has been moved to Dev Review
 This PR includes appropriate unit tests
 I have run and tested this change locally
 I have run the E2E tests on ths change against my local UI + API server with yarn test:local
 If this includes a UI change, I have taken screen recordings or screenshots of the new behavior and notified the PO and UX designer
 If this includes an API change, I have updated the appropriate Swagger definitions and notified API consumers
 If this includes a new feature flag, I have created and linked new JIRA tickets to (a) turn on the feature flag and (b) remove it later

commit.message: was sometimes not finding a matched institution

nodes.bodyText: nit: maybe indicate in the help text or hover  text that  this applies to  all workspaces owned by this user.
nit: type these? I don't know what rule we settled on for when we explicitly type stuff.
I'm not sure if we want to tolerate undefined values or just assume we'll set whatever isn't there to null. IOW I never understood how undefined is a feature of JavaScript.
nit: I'd name this isAboveLimit. Generally booleans starting with forms of "be" are more recognizable IMO.

render implies a side effect. I'd call this formatCreditUsage. (The negative to zero conversion indicates to me that maybe we shouldn't put it in a public utils file, as that's not standard, and would be an easy way to generate bugs.)
Is there a specific requirement to drop the cents when it's zero? Why not when it's $1? Or can we just round to the nearest dollar?
direct comparison to undefined makes me nervous. Is everything getting initialized correctly?
nit: don't think you need the curly braces for a string literal with no interpolation.
nit: if the value is exactly 0, it will print as $0.00 but if negative it's $0?
